316–Deceased","1316":"1316","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1453":"1453","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Powell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Hywel</i> ‘son of <i>Hywel</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘eminent’ (see   Howell  ).","Irish: mainly of Welsh origin as in 1 above, but sometimes a surname adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phóil</b> ‘son of the servant of Saint Paul’ (see   Guilfoyle  ).","English: variant of   Paul   or   Poole  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Powel","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Powell  .","North German: from a form of the personal name   Paul  ."]},{"name":"Howell","meanings":["Welsh and English: in the Welsh border counties, from the Welsh male personal name <i>Hywel</i> ‘eminent’, popular since the Middle Ages particularly in honor of the great 10th-century law-giving Welsh king. The name may also arise from the Breton personal name <i>Houuel</i>, <i>Huwel</i>, <i>Huwal</i>, <i>Howael</i>, cognate with the Welsh name. Bretons were especially numerous in the eastern counties of England. See   Powell  .","English: perhaps from a Middle English personal name <i>Huwel</i> (spelled <i>Howel</i>), a shortening of <i>Huwelot</i> or <i>Huelin</i> (see   Hewlett   and   Huling  ), both pet forms of Middle English <i>Huw</i> (see   Hugh  ).","English: habitational name from Howell (Lincolnshire), from an uncertain initial element + Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’."]},{"name":"Powles","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of <b>Powells</b>, itself a variant of   Powell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Hywell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’